^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let us discuss Spencer's splinter bid. When partner opens 1 of a major, a double jump in a suit is called a splinter. It shows an opening hand (13-16 dummy points) with 4 trump and a singleton (usually) or a void (occasionally) in the bid suit.|
PG| ***** 48 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Over 1@S -- 4@C, 4@D, and 4H are splinter bids.
Over 1@H - 3@S, 4@C, and 4@D are splinter bids. They are very descriptive.|
PG| ***** 49 ***** |


AT| Let us look at when should opener consider slam?|
PG| ***** 50 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The idea is that you need a good "fit" and that means in this case it depends on what Bonnie has in hearts. She does not want wasted HCP in hearts. The ace is not wasted, because it takes care of the singleton. But the @HK @HQ and @HJ are all wasted, because they do not fit well with partner. The best holding to have over a splinter is either 3 or 4 small, or 3 or 4 to the ace. The @HQ in Bonnie's hand was wasted, plus she had a minimum opener, so she clearly did not want to go on.|
PG| ***** 51 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|However, let's move a couple of cards around. Change the HA to the CA, and the @HQ to the @DK. In that case Bonnie only has 1 more point, 12 HCP, but slam is cold because of the excellent heart holding, with no wasted HCP. Please remember, if pard spinsters, you must discount all high cards in the splinter suit other than the ace. And you also must discount shortness (doubleton or singleton). You want small cards in the splinter suit so you can generate tricks by ruffing which is why I said 3 or 4 small is ideal.|
PG| ***** 52 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Splinters are nice bids, and you should make them when appropriate. However, they do have the one disadvantage that they take up a lot of bidding space. So you should not splinter with a strong hand that might have slam any way. A good rule, recommended by Bergen, is you should have 13-16 dummy points to splinter, no more. That way, partner knows your hand is limited, and can judge accordingly. |
PG| ***** 53 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Therefore, Spencer was border line in terms of almost being too strong. He has 14 HCP, 1 length point, and 3 for the singleton, which gives him 18. So if he chose 2N, that would be fine. However, what then happens is, over 2N, Bonnie bids 4S. That shows 12-14 HCP and no singletons or voids. Then Spencer is left to wonder if the singleton heart is enough to make slam. Not bidding a splinter is a two-edged sword.|
