^-|CP||FP||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BMart Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|I’ve found these doubles to be essential when you are trying to get to 3NT after an opponent’s preempt. Although Thrump Doubles are not yet well-known, their intent is very similar to the popular convention Western Cue-bids.|
PG| ***** 117 ***** |


AT|

The phrase "Thrump Doubles" was coined by World Champion Eric Rodwell by deleting the six middle letters in the phrase, THRee notrUMP. Eric used this term to define certain doubles in Precision. He found Thrump Doubles to be especially useful when a player was hoping to play in 3NT, but lacked a stopper in the suit that an opponent had bid.|
PG| ***** 118 ***** |


AT|

I agree with Eric; that on certain auctions, a double is needed to ask partner to bid 3NT with a stopper in the opponent’s suit. The two auctions where I feel Thrump Doubles are most necessary are:|
PG| ***** 119 ***** |


AT|

1. Partner opens one of a suit; an opponent jumps to 3D, 3H, or 3S; and responder doubles.  (Normal Negative Doubles are used after 3C.)

2. The auction begins with an opponent’s 3-level preempt, and you (or your partner) doubles.|
PG| ***** 120 ***** |


AT|

Why try so hard to get to 3NT after their preempt?|
PG| ***** 121 ***** |


AT|

In a suit contract, ruffs or bad trump splits are often fatal. Meanwhile, because the preemptor probably has no entry, 3NT rates to play like a dream. In fact, not only should you prefer 3NT rather than 5C or 5D, but you should also prefer 3NT to game in a major suit!|
PG| ***** 122 ***** |


AT|

Thrump Doubles say nothing about unbid suits. The doubler may have great length/strength in a minor, but he lacks a stopper in the opponent’s suit. On most hands, opener has a stopper and will bid 3NT. With no stopper, he’ll do the best he can. Unless your opponents stop preempting, or you like playing in 5C and 5D, you don’t want to play bridge without Thrump Doubles!|
PG| ***** 123 ***** |


